snippet.textDisplay:
For anyone who still believes Wilder won.

You can look at the fight anyway you won't but the correct way and the only way a judge should be scoring the fight is like this.

You need to give Wilder 10-8 round for both the knockdowns (even though some may argue that Fury was outboxing Wilder before & after the 12th round knockdown, so it should be a 10-9 round to Wilder). Personally I don't think Fury dominated enough of the 12th round to justify a 9-10 round.

Now even if you can find 2 other rounds that Wilder won (which most boxing experts believe he didn't win more then 1 other round) he still should have lost 112-114.
Wilder:10,10,9,9,9,9,9,9,10,9,9,10=112
Fury: 9,9,10,10,10,10,10,10,8,10,10,8 = 114

Judges should be looking for 4 different things to help determine which fighter won.

Effective Aggression: Wilder was being aggressive but it is was not effective because he was not landing shots and was getting countered way too often.

Ring Generalship: The fighter who controls the action and enforces his will and style. (It was easy to see that Fury controlled the action and enforced his style).

Defense: I don't think anyone will argue who was superior in this department.

Hard and Clean Punches: Even though Fury's punches are not as dangerous as Wilders, they should still have been scored as hard and clean punches. Whereas Wilder landed a few big bombs but most of his punches did not land clean.

snippet.textDisplay:
Imo opinion the only way Fury will get the TKO is to work the body. When he’s inside wilders arms go so high up. Yet I’ve not seen anyone work it yet.. also of note... because Wilder is such a big puncher... everyone is afraid to go to war with him. The way to beat Deontay Wilder is to stay on him. He can’t swing at you when your in close. His upper body strength is so powerful I believe makes his chin so strong. Weaken the support.. you can TKO Wilder when he’s arms are down. Look at the twelve round of the last fight... after he knocked Fury down his arms when so low... he was gassed and hurt. Fury should have jumped on him...
I don’t suspect Fury will have a mapped out plan as I beleive his best skill is to adapt to a fight but I’m sure his team will be preparing for the knock out next time.. get Wilder wound up in the first couple of rounds... box for the remaining rounds. After 6/8 rounds Fury could and I think he will take Wilder out this time.

snippet.textDisplay:
Fury was a cherry pick last time gone wrong. Was away from boxing for 3 years, ballooned to 450lb, and still won the fight. He wasn't his normal sharp self ,and less power too (although he's not a power puncher). I think this time around FURY will show that there is levels to this game, and break him down with a stoppage in the 8th or 9th. Obviously Wilder is a puncher and dangerous, but if you were gonna put your mortgage on one of the two, you'd most probably put your trust in Fury.
Wilder will not be finished though, but he will have to somewhat rebuild, and it's not easy with several really good current HWs and few up an coming beasts, too. He's like 34 or 35 now too, and unless he hurries up and takes the big challenges he wouldn't have really achieved much in boxing. He hasn't got a big name win on his resume in 43 fights.
